      "source": [
        "We analyzed what factors influence the interest rates borrowers are charged on their loans. Our findings provide a clear picture of what matters most to lenders.\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Overall Strength of the Analysis\n",
        "Our analysis explains almost 90% of the variation in interest rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "In simple terms: we can accurately predict interest rates based on borrower and loan characteristics.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Main Factors Affecting Interest Rates\n",
        "Credit Grade (Loan Risk)\n",
        "The biggest driver of interest rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Borrowers with lower grades pay higher rates. Example:\n",
        "\n",
        "Grade B → ~3.6% higher than Grade A\n",
        "\n",
        "Grade C → ~7% higher\n",
        "\n",
        "Grade G → ~21% higher\n",
        "\n",
        "Takeaway: Better credit grade = lower interest rate; worse credit grade = higher interest rate.\n",
        "\n",
        "Debt-to-Income Ratio\n",
        "Borrowers with more debt relative to their income pay higher interest rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is a strong indicator of risk, so lenders price accordingly.\n",
        "\n",
        "Credit Utilization\n",
        "Borrowers who use a large portion of their available credit (credit cards, lines of credit) face slightly higher rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Income\n",
        "Higher income leads to slightly lower interest rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Shows lenders value financial stability, but the effect is smaller than credit grade or debt levels.\n",
        "\n",
        "Employment Length\n",
        "Longer employment generally results in slightly lower rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Very short-term employment (<1 year) can slightly increase rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Loan Amount\n",
        "Larger loans have a small impact, slightly increasing interest rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. Big Picture\n",
        "Credit grade is the dominant factor influencing interest rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Debt management (debt-to-income ratio, credit utilization) also matters.\n",
        "\n",
        "Income, employment, and loan size play smaller roles but still affect rates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Lenders’ decisions are strongly risk-based, reflecting borrowers’ ability to repay.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. Business Implications\n",
        "Borrowers can improve rates by:\n",
        "\n",
        "Maintaining or improving credit grades\n",
        "\n",
        "Managing debt levels\n",
        "\n",
        "Keeping consistent employment\n",
        "\n",
        "Lenders can target products or communicate with borrowers based on these factors.\n",
        "\n",
        "Bottom Line:\n",
        "Interest rates are primarily determined by risk and financial health. Borrowers with better credit, lower debt, and stable income/employment are rewarded with lower rates, while higher-risk borrowers face higher rates."
      ]
