        "It misses half the positives. Out of 254 real \"1\" cases, the model only found 126 of them. It silently missed 128. Depending on what \"1\" represents (fraud, a disease, a defect), those misses could be very costly.\n",
        "Precision is only 2.9%. When the model does predict \"1\", it's wrong 97% of the time — generating 4,238 false alarms for every 126 real catches. In practice this means anyone acting on those predictions would be chasing ghosts almost constantly.\n",
        "Why this happens: The dataset is heavily imbalanced — roughly 50,128 cases are \"0\" but only 254 are \"1\". The model took the easy path and learned to say \"no\" most of the time. That's why accuracy looks high even though the model is barely useful for catching the thing you actually care about.\n",
        "The model is good at normal cases but bad at rare ones. We need to either retrain it with balanced data, use a different decision threshold, or look at a metric like F1-score instead of accuracy."
